    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between wine pairings for gas versus charcoal BBQ?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Charcoal BBQ imparts more intense smoky flavors that pair beautifully with bold, tannic red wines like Cabernet Sauvignon or Syrah, which can match the char and smoke intensity. Gas grilling produces cleaner flavors with less smoke, making it more versatile for medium-bodied wines like Pinot Noir or even crisp whites like Albariño. The cooking method directly impacts which wine characteristics will complement versus compete with your BBQ flavors.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine chilled at outdoor BBQ parties?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, serve both reds and whites slightly cooler than normal indoor serving temperatures since outdoor heat will warm them quickly. Chill reds to 60-65°F (they'll warm to perfect drinking temperature of 65-68°F outdoors) and keep whites ice-cold at 45-50°F in insulated containers. Consider bringing wines indoors 30 minutes before serving if they've been stored in hot cars or garages, as excessive heat can damage wine flavors permanently.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which wines work best with spicy BBQ rubs and sauces?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Off-dry wines with touch of sweetness are your best defense against spicy heat - try German Riesling, Gewürztraminer, or Portuguese Vinho Verde to cool the palate. For red wine lovers, choose fruit-forward options with lower tannins like Beaujolais, Côtes du Rhône, or New World Merlot, as high tannins amplify spice burn. Avoid bone-dry wines and high-alcohol bottles, which intensify heat sensations rather than providing relief.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is wine with BBQ good for beginners who don't usually drink wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely - BBQ's bold, familiar flavors make it one of the best entry points for wine beginners since the food won't be overshadowed by unfamiliar wine tastes. Start with approachable, fruit-forward wines like Zinfandel, Malbec, or Moscato that complement BBQ's sweet and savory elements. The casual, social nature of BBQ also removes intimidation factors, allowing newcomers to focus on enjoying the pairing rather than worrying about "proper" wine etiquette.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for BBQ?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is selecting wines that are too delicate or subtle for BBQ's intense flavors - light Pinot Grigio or elegant Burgundy will be completely overwhelmed by smoky ribs or tangy sauce. Another major mistake is not considering the sauce and seasonings, focusing only on the protein; a wine that pairs perfectly with plain chicken will clash horribly with spicy dry rub or sweet molasses-based sauce. Always match wine intensity to the overall dish intensity, including all flavor components.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic wine alternatives that work with BBQ?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, several non-alcoholic options complement BBQ beautifully - try dealcoholized red wines from producers like Ariel or Fre, which retain wine-like tannins and complexity. Sparkling grape juices, especially unsweetened versions, provide acidity that cuts through rich BBQ fats similarly to wine. For unique alternatives, consider kombucha with fruit flavors or shrubs (drinking vinegars) mixed with sparkling water, which offer the acidity and complexity that make wine such a natural BBQ partner.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I find good value wines specifically for BBQ entertaining?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for bold, food-friendly regions that offer excellent quality-to-price ratios: Portuguese Douro reds, Spanish Jumilla, or Washington State Syrah typically deliver BBQ-friendly intensity under $15. Buy by the case from these regions during sales for additional savings, and don't overlook bag-in-box wines for large gatherings - quality producers like Black Box or Bota Box offer consistent, BBQ-appropriate wines at exceptional per-glass value. Focus on wines designed for food pairing rather than sipping alone.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I use leftover BBQ wine for cooking the next day?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely - wine that's been open for 1-2 days is perfect for BBQ marinades, deglazing pans, or making wine-based BBQ sauces since cooking concentrates and transforms the flavors anyway. Store opened wine in the refrigerator with a cork or wine stopper to slow oxidation, and use within 3-4 days for cooking applications. Red wines work particularly well in BBQ glazes and marinades, while white wine is excellent for deglazing after grilling vegetables or making compound butters.</p>
